**No — not reliably.** Right now duplicate emails are not handled with a clear “this email is already registered” message.

## What the app does today

In [`SignupForm.tsx`](src/components/auth/SignupForm.tsx):

```37:43:src/components/auth/SignupForm.tsx
    if (signUpError) {
      setError(signUpError.message);
      return;
    }

    setSuccess(true);
    router.refresh();
```

It only shows an error when Supabase returns `signUpError`. On success it always shows **“Check your email”**.

## What Supabase actually does

With **Confirm email ON** (your setup), Supabase **usually does not error** on duplicate sign-ups. That’s intentional — it avoids letting attackers probe whether an email is registered.

Instead it often returns:
- `error: null` (looks successful)
- A user object with **`identities.length === 0`** when the email already exists

So your app shows the green “Check your email” message even when the account already exists — which is misleading.

| Scenario | What user sees now |
|----------|-------------------|
| New email | “Check your email” ✓ |
| Email already registered (confirm email ON) | Still “Check your email” ✗ |
| Supabase returns an explicit error | Red error with `signUpError.message` ✓ |

## How to fix it (recommended)

After `signUp`, also inspect `data`:

```typescript
const { data, error: signUpError } = await supabase.auth.signUp({ ... });

if (signUpError) {
  setError(signUpError.message);
  return;
}

if (data.user && data.user.identities?.length === 0) {
  setError("An account with this email already exists. Try logging in instead.");
  return;
}

setSuccess(true);
```

That gives a clear message without relying on Supabase exposing duplicate emails in the error field.

---

If you want this implemented, switch to Agent mode (or say “add it”) and I can update `SignupForm.tsx` for you.

[REDACTED]

